<pre class="bz_comment_text">Created <span class=""><a href="attachment.cgi?id=203580" name="attach_203580" title="patch to make connections fail if ssl-strict is set but no ssl-ca-file is used">attachment 203580</a> <a href="attachment.cgi?id=203580&amp;action=edit" title="patch to make connections fail if ssl-strict is set but no ssl-ca-file is used">[details]</a></span> <a href="review?bug=666280&amp;attachment=203580">[review]</a>
patch to make connections fail if ssl-strict is set but no ssl-ca-file is used

The current behavior of libsoup is that if there is no ssl-ca-file set but ssl-strict is set to True it will accept any certificate. While technically it makes sense I think its not what most users expect when reading the API documentation for ssl-strict.

I think a better default is that if there is no ssl-ca-file and ssl-strict is set it should fail any ssl connection. So that its a conscious decision by the developer to turn it off. 

I attach a very basic patch for this. Alternatively it could be a different error code with a message like "ERROR: ssl-strict checking requested but no ssl-ca-file provided" (that requires some more work though).</pre>
